title: I’ve been thinking about Endgame
body:
I’ve been thinking about Endgame over the last few days and I have to say, I really miss the Guardians of the Galaxy in the equation. Especially Peter Quill. 

He’s just another human, but in a universe of superheroes this makes him the most likeable and relatable character I think.  

Because he’ll let you know when you’re talking bullshit. Because he’s not your classic just-smash-the-thing kind of guy but instead always comes up with this genius kinda improvised move that will go wrong in some parts but will go mostly right otherwise. Because he’s got no superpowers, no extra strength, no crazy tech, no visible special talent, and still he and his team always makes it through. Because he has so much to lose, like not only his love interest, but also his four (!) friends, his spaceship, or his mother’s music tape. Because him processing the grief of his most recent loss would make a great character arc. Because his emotions are raw, and he’s hurt, and he’s flawed, and yeah there’s something about him that makes him the most real of them all. 

I like him a lot. I like his team a lot. Of all the Marvel characters, he managed to touch me most emotionally. Because I can identify with his not-superhero-ness, I guess. He’s someone who loves and holds onto things dearly, and that makes him incredibly vulnerable. I love that so much about him. 

Characterwise, Tony and Peter aren’t a great combo - I realized that as soon as they got some screentime together in Infinity War. And of course, when in doubt Tony was the choice to keep, but yet…I wish Peter was still there as well. His space knowledge could have been useful to the others, since it is of a different nature than Thor’s…plus I need someone to mix up this dead-stern group of Avengers :) It’s why they kept Rocket, I suppose. Go, Rocket, and blast ‘em! :D

summary: okay so my endgame theory is:
body:
okay so my endgame theory is:

marvel are a bunch of liars and in the infinity war promo they made it look like cap or tony were gonna die and leave all the newbies to fight thanos..

so in the endgame trailer i think tony’s ‘part of the journey is the end’ speech is there to make us feel a certain dread that tony won’t survive this movie. additionally, with the spiderman: far from home promotions tony isn’t going to feature in any of that bc it would be a spoiler for his fate in avengers: endgame (obviously).. therefore by not adding him in far from home, when he played such a crucial role to peter parker’s story in homecoming, it makes the fans think he isn’t going to survive endgame.

so my point is could this all just be a tactic to make us think tony is going to be the one to sacrifice himself? seeing as he is the longest serving mcu character and all we know is that he’s stuck on a doomed spaceship, when in actual fact it’s a marketing ploy to divert us from the real plot of the story, and the real sacrifices that are going to be made


(or this could just be me lying to myself and coming up with reasons for why Tony won’t die)
